1131","1126–1211":"1126–1211","1024–1096":"1024–1096","1025–Female":"1025–Deceased","1126":"1126","1137":"1137","1025":"1025","1024":"1024","1211":"1211","1056":"1056","1121":"1121","2 MAY 1131":"2 May 1131","1131":"1131","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","Wickrath, Herzogtum Geldern, Saint-Empire romain":"Wickrath, Guelders","Hochstadt (Pfalz), RP Germany":"Hochstadt (Pfalz), Südliche Weinstraße, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Hochstaden, Rheinland, Germany":"Rhineland, Prussia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Gerhard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gerhard II. von Hochstaden was born in 1056, in Rhineland, Prussia, his father, Gerhard von Hochstaden I, was 32 and his mother, Heilwig von Lothringen, was 32. He had at least 2 daughters with Aleydis von Wickrath. He died in 1137, at the age of 81."},"et":{"1056–1137":"1056–1137","1060–1121":"1060–1121","1075–1131":"1075–1131","1126–1211":"1126–1211","1024–1096":"1024–1096","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","1126":"1126","1137":"1137","1025":"1025","1024":"1024","1211":"1211","1056":"1056","1121":"1121","2 MAY 1131":"2. mai 1131","1131":"1131","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","Wickrath, Herzogtum Geldern, Saint-Empire romain":"Wickrath, Geldern","Hochstadt (Pfalz), RP Germany":"Hochstadt (Pfalz), Südliche Weinstraße, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Hochstaden, Rheinland, Germany":"Rheinprovinz, Preußen"},"fi":{"1056–1137":"1056–1137","1060–1121":"1060–1121","1075–1131":"1075–1131","1126–1211":"1126–1211","1024–1096":"1024–1096","1025–Female":"1025–Kuollut","1126":"1126","1137":"1137","1025":"1025","1024":"1024","1211":"1211","1056":"1056","1121":"1121","2 MAY 1131":"2. toukokuuta 1131","1131":"1131","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","Wickrath, Herzogtum Geldern, Saint-Empire romain":"Wickrath, Geldern","Hochstadt (Pfalz), RP Germany":"Hochstadt (Pfalz)